Medallion architecture — what belongs in each layer.

Three layers, each with a single job, and the exam tests recognising which layer a description fits into.

Bronze is raw, append-only, and replayable. One table per source, the schema mirrors the source — nested data is fine — strings and nulls are allowed, and quality is deliberately not enforced here. Bronze is your audit copy.

Silver is cleaned, conformed, and deduplicated. It stays at the same grain as bronze — one row per event — but the types are pinned, nulls in required columns are dropped, the foreign keys are conformed, and quality rules are now enforced, through expectations or check constraints.

Gold is business-ready, aggregated, and served. It's a star schema or a wide rollup, ready for business intelligence or machine learning. It's often pre-aggregated — by day, or per customer — so a gold row is one per business entity, not one per event.

The key principle for gold — prefer many narrow, purpose-built tables over one giant catch-all table.
